<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=997061017186></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f997061017186><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj><a href=/strategy/classes.html?class=1&mid=997061017186>RE: skills</a></span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Aug 5th 9:23 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>As for whether dual-weild or two-handed is better, it depends on the situation. If you need to do a lot of damage and hit constantly to keep the monster on you and off the cleric and wizard, use two one-handed weapons. I'd recommend you put the faster weapon in your main hand, as how often you attack with both weapons is affected by how often you attack with your main hand.<br><br>Two-handers are still useful, though. If you're fighting something with a high-powered damage shield, you don't want to dual wield. More attacks means more damage from the damage shield. That's where the big sword you bought comes in- It does a little less total damage than dual wield, in less hits. Less hits means less damage from the damage shield, which means less cleric heals, or downtime if you're soloing.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>

</ul>

</ul>
<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99669760562684></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99669760562684><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj><a href=/strategy/classes.html?class=1&mid=99669760562684>re: wondering</a></span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?id=81241><span id= >Spleenventor</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>1 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Aug 1st 4:26 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Working those other combat skills, 1hb, 2hs, 2hb, pierce is going to be tough. You need to get alot of practice in against mobs that are experience generating to improve those. I would suggest that you try to do that as the main tank in a fair sized group. Your main function in that situation is tho soak up damage and taunt, so you can afford to practice your extra weapon skills without risking your level. <br><br>Another (possibly slower) method is to work on the mob with your high skill weapon, then once it goes below half hp, switch to the lower skill weapon. It will take longer to kill, and it may not hit the morale break point as fast, but the point is to get practice in against a tough opponent.<br><br>I have heard that you can't improve against greens, but that isn't my experience. I think the number of attempts is the main factor in achiveing the skill increase. If you only attack greens which may only take one or two swings to kill you will not see a rapid improvement. However, I have improved my archery skill and throwing skills by a shoot and sit method.<br><br>I shoot the mob, it attacks me, I beat it to the break point, then I plink an arrow at it as it runs off, I sit down until it turns back toward me, then I stand and plink another arrow at it, and repeat til it is dead or one blow from death. Works with a high delay or low delay bow.<br><br>I ahve also found that if I take on several greens at once, switch targets as one breaks, I can work my skill up a bit as they recycle through the break, recover, attack, break. Works best with 3 mobs. <br><br>Hope this is of some use.<br><br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>

</ul>
